Example
Check whether a variable is of type float or not:
<?php
$a = 32;
echo "a is " . is_double($a) . "<br>";
$b = 0;
echo "b is 
  " . is_double($b) . "<br>";
$c = 32.5;
echo "c is " . is_double($c) . 
  "<br>";
$d = "32";
echo "d is " . is_double($d) . "<br>";
$e = 
  true;
echo "e is " . is_double($e) . "<br>";
$f = "null";
echo "f 
  is " . is_double($f) . "<br>";
$g = 1.e3;
echo "g is " . is_double($g) 
  . "<br>";
?>

Definition and Usage
The is_double() function checks whether a variable is of type float or not.
This function is an alias of
is_float()
.
Syntax
is_double(
variable
);
Parameter Values
Parameter
Description
variable
Required. Specifies the variable to check
Technical Details
Return Value:
TRUE if
variable
is a float, FALSE otherwise
Return Type:
Boolean
PHP Version:
4.0+

